3p0.title: Bit (of information)
3p0.text:
[summary: A bit of information is the amount of information required to single out one object from a set of two. That is, a bit is the amount of information carried by the answer to a yes-or-no question. If you want to single out one of the hands of one of your biological grandparents (such as the left hand of your paternal grandmother), you can do that with three bits of information: One to single out "left hand" or "right hand", one to single out "maternal" or "paternal", and one to single out "grandfather" or "grandmother". We can also speak of storing information in physical systems which can be put into multiple states: A coin can be used to store a single bit of information (by placing it either heads or tails); a normal six-sided die can be used to store a little over [3ty 2.5 bits] of information. In general, a message that singles out one thing from a set of $n$ is defined to contain [3nd $\log_2(n)$] bits of information.]

A bit of information (not to be confused with a [bit_of_evidence bit of evidence]) is the amount of information required to single out one object from a set of two. That is, a bit is the amount of information carried by the answer to a yes-or-no question. If you want to single out one of the hands of one of your biological grandparents (such as the left hand of your paternal grandmother), you can do that with three bits of information: One to single out "left hand" or "right hand", one to single out "maternal" or "paternal", and one to single out "grandfather" or "grandmother". We can also speak of storing information in physical systems which can be put into multiple states: A coin can be used to store a single bit of information (by placing it either heads or tails); a normal six-sided die can be used to store a little over [3ty 2.5 bits] of information. In general, a message that singles out one thing from a set of $n$ is defined to contain [3nd $\log_2(n)$] bits of information.

Bits can be defined in terms of [-entropy], in which case one bit is the difference between the [-entropy] of a [uniform_distribution uniform distribution] over a [-binary] [-random_variable variable] and the entropy of a [probability_distribution probability distribution] that assigns probability 1 to a single value. We can also define information without appealing to entropy (which is important if we want to instead define entropy in terms of information); this definition is somewhat more involved, because it requires formalizing what it means "single out" an object using a message. See the page on [information_theory_formalization formalizing information theory] for more details.

"Bit" is a portmanteau of "binary digit", "binary" because it is the amount of information required to single out one thing from a set of 2. The choice of 2 is arbitrary; analogous units of information exist for each number. For example, a [3ww] is the amount of information it takes to single out one thing from a set of three, a [3wn] is the amount of information it takes to single out one thing from a set of ten, and so on. It is easy to convert between bases, for example, a decit is $\log_2(10) \approx 3.32$ bits, because it takes a little over three bits to pick one thing out from a set of 10. See also the pages on [ converting between units of information] and [3ty fractional bits].

The amount of information you can transmit (or store) grows [exponential exponentially] in the number of bits at your disposal. For example, consider a punch card that can hold ten bits of information. You can use one punch card to pick out a single thing from a set of $2^{10}=1024.$ From two punch cards you can pick out a single thing from a set of $2^{20}=1048576.$ The number of _things you can distinguish_ using two punch cards is 1024 times larger than the number of things you can distinguish with one punch card, and the amount of _information you can encode_ using two punch cards is precisely twice as much (20 bits) as the amount of information you can encode using one punch card (10 bits).

In other words, you can single out one object from a collection of $n$ (or store a number between 1 and $n$) using [3nd $\log_2(n)$] bits of information. You can sometimes communicate using fewer bits, if the person you're communicating with already has some information about which object you want to single out. For more on what it means for a physical system to "have information," and what it means for them to "communicate" (in a precise formal sense), and how to measure the amount of information necessary to transmit different messages between systems with different amounts of information, see [-3qq].
